Title

Implement MongoDB Verification Tests for Third-Party Synchronization Flow (Local)

Background

Current Journey Tests do not validate whether Third-Party configuration changes are persisted correctly in MongoDB after synchronization. As a result, successful test execution does not guarantee that the expected runtime state has been created, updated, or removed.

This story introduces database-level validation to verify synchronization outcomes directly.

Objective

Implement Playwright-based integration tests that validate MongoDB state after Third-Party synchronization.

Scope

In Scope

* Playwright test implementation
* MongoDB state verification
* Local environment execution
* Test data setup and cleanup

Out of Scope

* Union environment implementation
* Rehearsal environment implementation
* Pipeline/Drivetrain changes
* Journey Test removal/migration
* Changes to sync business logic
* Changes to OBA configuration structure

Acceptance Criteria

AC1 – Create Validation

Given a new TPP is added to configuration

When synchronization executes

Then a MongoDB record is created with the expected:

* TPP ID
* Client ID
* Status
* Permissions/Scopes

AC2 – Update Validation

Given an existing TPP exists in MongoDB

When permissions/scopes are updated in configuration and synchronization executes

Then MongoDB reflects the updated values

AC3 – Delete Validation

Given an existing TPP exists in MongoDB

When the TPP is removed from configuration and synchronization executes

Then the corresponding MongoDB record is removed (or marked inactive as per current implementation)

AC4 – Idempotency Validation

Given no configuration changes

When synchronization executes multiple times

Then no duplicate MongoDB records are created

Definition of Done

* Playwright tests implemented
* MongoDB assertions implemented
* Local execution successful
* Test data cleanup implemented
* Test evidence attached to Jira
